{"questionId":"22535","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Three points&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;lie on the plane&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Π</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Plane <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Π</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> has equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The plane <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Π</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>. The line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> and the plane <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Π</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> intersect at the point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that at the point&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>λ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>substitutes the equation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> into the equation of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Π</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>λ</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>λ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>⇒</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>λ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>λ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22535","referenceCode":"21N.2.AHL.TZ0.11c.i","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that at the point P, λ=34.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.12—Vector definitions","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.13—Scalar (dot) product","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.14—Vector equation of line","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.16—Vector product","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.17—Vector equations of a plane","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.18—Intersections of lines & planes"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}